<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880815-0019 </DOCNO><HL> Ex-Aide of Barclays Unit Sentenced in Bribery Case </HL><SO> </SO><CO> BCS FREST </CO><DATELINE> HONG KONG  </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former executive director of Barclays Asia Ltd., Stuart Turner, was sentenced to one year in jail on two counts of accepting a bribe, the Independent Commission Against Corruption said.    In an appearance before Judge Owen Corcoran Tuesday, Mr. Turner, 41 years old, pleaded guilty to accepting 888,000 Hong Kong dollars (US$114,000) in July 1981 from George Tan, chairman of the bankrupt Carrian group, as a reward for arranging a loan of HK$100 million for Carrian Holdings Ltd.    He also had admitted receiving HK$300,000 from businessman Victor Hwang in March 1982 in return for arranging an HK$80 million loan for Mr. Hwang's Tri-View Ltd.    Judge Corcoran Friday ordered Mr. Turner to pay HK$888,000 to the liquidator of Carrian Holdings and fined him a further HK$300,000, the commission against corruption said.    Barclays Asia has been a non-operating unit of Barclays Bank PLC of Britain for a number of years, according to Barclays in London. </TEXT></DOC>